---
import Layout from "../../../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import CapitalGainsTaxCalculator from "../../../../components/CapitalGainsTaxCalculator.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="Capital Gains Tax Calculator (Canada) | CRA Inclusion Rates"
  description="Estimate your Canadian capital gains tax. Understand how the 50% inclusion rate affects your taxable income and marginal tax rate."
>
  <main class="flex-grow pt-24 pb-20">
    <!-- Title Section -->
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 mb-8 text-center sm:text-left">
      <h1 class="text-3xl font-extrabold text-white tracking-tight font-sans">
        Capital Gains Tax Calculator (Canada)
      </h1>
      <p class="text-sm text-slate-400 mt-2 max-w-2xl leading-relaxed">
        Model your potential CRA tax liability using the standard 50% inclusion rate for Canadian residents.
      </p>
    </div>

    <!-- Calculator Component -->
    <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
      <CapitalGainsTaxCalculator defaultCountry="CA" />
    </div>

    <!-- Explainer Content -->
    <div class="border-t border-slate-800/60 mt-12 bg-gradient-to-b from-slate-950 to-slate-950/95">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto py-16 px-4">
        <section>
          <div class="mb-6">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Understanding Canadian Capital Gains Tax</h2>
            <p class="text-slate-400 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-4">
              In Canada, you do not pay tax on the entire profit you make from selling an asset. Instead, only a portion of the gain is included in your taxable income.
            </p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-5 text-sm text-slate-400 space-y-2 mb-4">
              <li><strong>Inclusion Rate:</strong> Currently, the standard inclusion rate is 50%. This means only half of your capital gain is taxable.</li>
              <li><strong>Marginal Tax Rates:</strong> The taxable portion of your gain is added to your other income for the year and taxed at your marginal federal and provincial tax rates.</li>
              <li><strong>Capital Losses:</strong> Capital losses can only be used to offset capital gains, not ordinary income. They can be carried back 3 years or carried forward indefinitely.</li>
            </ul>
            <p class="text-slate-400 text-sm leading-relaxed mb-6">
              For a comprehensive guide on minimizing these taxes, check out our <a href="/blog/capital-gains-tax-canada/" class="text-[#00F5D4] hover:underline">Canadian Capital Gains Tax Guide</a>.
            </p>
            <p class="text-xs text-slate-500 italic">
              Source: <a href="https://www.canada.ca/en/revenue-agency/services/tax/individuals/topics/about-your-tax-return/tax-return/completing-a-tax-return/personal-income/line-12700-capital-gains.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="hover:text-slate-300 underline">CRA - Line 12700 Capital Gains</a>.
            </p>
          </div>
        </section>
      </div>
    </div>
  </main>

  <script type="application/ld+json" slot="head">
    {
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How much is the capital gains tax in Canada?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Canada does not have a specific 'capital gains tax rate'. Instead, 50% of your capital gain is included in your income and taxed at your marginal tax rate."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the capital gains inclusion rate?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The inclusion rate determines what portion of a capital gain is taxable. The standard rate is 50%, meaning half the profit is tax-free."
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  </script>
</Layout>
